column168: WHEN LOADING FREIGHT ONTO TRAILER, FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS PUSHING DRUM AND SOMETHING PROTRUDING FROM FLOOR PUNCTURED THE DRUM ON BOTTOM.  DRUM WAS PLACED ON SIDE AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE MOVING FREIGHT ON DOCK, FORKLIFT OPERATOR NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE UNDER PALLET THAT THIS DRUM WAS ON.  REMOVED DRUM AND TURNED OVER AND FOUND THAT A NAIL ON THE PALLET THAT THE SHIPPER SUPPLIED, HAD PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  PLACED DRUM IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND ARE AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHEN UNLOADING TRAILER THE DOCKWORKER FOUND ONE SMALL POLY DRUM LAYING ON IT'S SIDE ON A PALLET WITH A SMALL PUDDLE UNDER IT.  HE UPRIGHTED DRUM AND COULD NOT FIND ANY PLACE ON THE DRUM WHERE IT WAS LEAKING FROM.  WE STILL PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

AT THIS POINT WE PREPARED THE DRUM FOR SHIPPING AND MOVED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.
CENTRAL'S HOSE RUPTURED.

DURING THE LOADING OF TRAILER, IT STARTED TO LEAK PRODUCT THRU THE OUTER BELLY SKIN OF TRAILER. PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED BACK INTO STORAGE. FACILITY HANDLED THE CONTAINMENT & CLEAN UP OF PRODUCT. TRAILER CLEANED & TAKEN TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION & CORRECTIVE REPAIRS.

DRIVER WAS MAKING RIGHT TURN FROM ARCO REFINERY ONTO FIRESTONE BLVD. SMALL CAR ATTEMPTED TO PASS TRUCK ON RIGHT.  HIT PLUMBING UNDERNEATH TRAILER CAUSING LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT IN PLUMBING.  DRIVER FELT IMPACT. EXITED CAB, WENT TO REAR OF TRAILER TO ACCESS DAMAGE.  IMMEDIATELY DAMMED FLOW OF PRODUCT WITH EMERGENCY ON BOARD SPILL KIT.  OTHER DRIVER LEFT THE SCENE.  DRIVER NOTIFIED DISPATCH AND MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL.  POLICE APPREHENDED OTHER PARTY.  WE ARE CURRENTLY WAITING FOR POLICE REPORT.  DENNIS YOUNG OF ARCO PRODUCTS COMPANY WAS BEHIND TRUCK AND WITNESSED ENTIRE INCIDENT.  COOL TRANSPORTS DRIVER PERFORMED EXACTLY AS EXPECTED.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL.

column168: ON OCTOBER 1, 2000, AT 15:00, UTLX 30010, A LOADED TANK CAR OF ACETONE, WAS FOUND LEAKING IN RADNOR YARD BY CSXT PERSONNEL IN NASHVILLE, TENNESSEE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 3 DROPS PER SECOND FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE CAP WAS TIGHT.  A CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER OPENED AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND THE GASKET CLEANED AND REPLACED. THE CAR WAS CONFIRMED AS NOT LEAKING AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

CSXT'S TRAIN Q31630 WAS PASSING THROUGH MASON CITY, WV, WHEN A CITIZEN OBSERVED A "CLOUD" COMING FROM THE TOP OF A TANK CAR NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAIN.  THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO CSXT; THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED & INSPECTED.  TANK CAR, RCRX 1078, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WAS FOUND TO BE SMOKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT ON THE SIDING AT GRAHAM, WV.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER OF THE RESIDUE CAR RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT ALL THE FILL LINE PHLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE, "NOT EVEN FINGER TIGHT".  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND CAR SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.

T/C DUPX 29712, LOAD ETHYLENE GLYCOL, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN HUMPED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN HAMLET, N.C..  THE T/C WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND DETERMINED THAT THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE PLUG WAS NOT THREADED PROPERLY TO SECURE THE APPURTENANCE.  THE SHIPPER RETAPPED THE THREADS OF THE VALVE ORIFICE AND REINSTALLED THE PLUG WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.

NOTIFIED OF LEAKING HAZ-MAT IN DOOR 34. UPON ARRIVAL, I DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A CORROSIVE LIQUID. I THEN RESPONDED ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE SHEET AND DECISION TREE. THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED. IT WAS THEN PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

column168: WHEN THE CONSIGNEE PLANT OPERATOR ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE TRAILER EXTERNAL VALVE THE VALVE STEM CAME OUT IN HIS HAND CAUSING APPROX TWO GALLON OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE CONSIGNEE CONTAINED UNLOADING RACK FLOOR.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE EXTERNAL VALVE STEM SADDLE COTTER PIN HAD BROKEN ALLOWING THE STEM TO COME ALL THE WAY OUT OF THE EXTERNAL VALVE QUICK REMOVE BONNET.  THE PLANT CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  WE SENT THE TRAILER TO A TRAILER REPAIR SHOP WHERE THEY REPLACED THE COTTER PIN, AND THE TRAILER RETURNED TO THE PLANT WHERE IT WAS UNLOADED WITH NO MORE PROBLEMS.

OPERATOR TERMINATED TRANSFER, CLEARED ALL LINES AND DISCONNECTED. OPERATOR THEN RECONNECTED TO A-END LIQUID VALVE AND RESUMED TRANSFER PROCESS WITHOUT INCIDENT. CAR WAS DEGASSED AND DEPRESSURIZED FOR REPAIRS. RELEASE WAS TO ATMOSPHERE ONLY AND DID NOT TRAVEL OFFSITE.

OHIO EPA MONITORAL CLEAN UP.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN A PACKAGE CAR AT SOUTH CENTER. WEARING P.P.E., I FOUND A BOX WITH A 5-PART HAZ-MAT PAPERWORK AND A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND STICKER ON IT. THE BOX WAS STAINED WITH LIQUID. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND CONTAINED BOX IN A SPILL TUB AND REMOVED IT TO HAZ-MAT AREA. 1 OF 6 PLASTIC 1/2 GAL. JUGS LEAKED DUE TO A BROKEN CAP. I PROCESSED THE WASTE THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM, AND REPACKAGED THE PRODUCTS IN A SALVAGE DRUM TO BE RTS.
REFERRING TO DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET, REMOVED CONTAINED LEAKING PKG FROM FEEDER. WEARING PROPER PPE, RETURNED TO DMP AREA TO PROCESS PROPERLY.

column168: UNLOADING TRAILER #485-6033 10/17/00 AT 0730. THE SHIPMENT CONSIGNING OF 15 BOXES WAS CRUSHED BY ANOTHER PALLET. 8 BOXES WERE LEAKING AND PUT INTO A HAZMAT DRUM LABELED

WHILE UNLOADING, A DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A PRIVATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND IS AWAITING PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE LID. THE LID WAS SECURED AND THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PROPERLY CLEANED UP. THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL AND IS AWAITING SHIPPER DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING OUR TANK TRAILER INTO STORAGE TANK, A CAP ON PUMP CAME OFF. THE PUMP WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY. PRODUCT RAN ONTO GROUND.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON SUNDAY (01OCT00) AFTERNOON AT 16:15 HOURS, ONE OF AAL (AMERICAN AIRLINES) WAREHOUSE CLERK DISCOVERED ONE OF NCA (NIPPON CARGO AIRLINES) STANDBY EXPORT CARGO UNIT STAGE INSIDE OF AAL WAREHOUSE WAS LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF PALLET (PAP2202KZ) THIS UNIT WAS OFF LOADED FROM KZ332/01OCT00 WHICH EN-ROUTE TO SAN FRANCISCO FROM LOS ANGLES (LAX) ON THE EARLY MORNING OF SUNDAY APPROXIMATELY 0335 HOURS. AFTER LEAKAGE WAS FOUND, AAL DUTY SUPERVISOR CONTACTED AIRPORT EMERGENCY TEAM AT 6-2323 AT 1645 HOURS. AIRPORT POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 1700 HOURS. THE HAZ MAT SPECIALIST ARRIVED AT 1735 HOURS AND INSPECTED ALL DOCUMENTS AND CONDITION ON PALLET. UNDER THE DIRECTION OF HAZMAT TEAM, THE AREA WAS SEALED-OFF APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET IN DIAMETER. AT 1745 HOURS, THE DAMAGED PLASTIC DRUM WAS REMOVED BY EAGLE/FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (CHEMTREC). AT 1815 HOURS ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE SEGREGATED AND REMOVED FROM OTHER DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENTS LOADED ON THE SAME PALLET. FIRE DEPARTMENT, HAZ MAT TEAM, AND AIRPORT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WERE PRESENT AT THE SCENE UNTIL TASK WAS COMPLETED BY EAGLE/FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING NB ON US HWY 99 APPROXIMATELY 25 MILES SOUTH OF BAKERSFIELD,CA. DRIVER REACHED TO ADJUST FAN SWITCH ON HEATER CONTROL. THE TRUCK DRIFTED OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER.DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO RECOVER AND OVER-CORRECTED, CAUSING REAR TRAILER TO LOSE CONTROL AND ROLL OVER. DIESEL FUEL LEAKED FROM TRAILER, IGNITED, CAUSING TRAILER & TRUCK TO BURN COMPLETELY.

LEAKAGE THROUGH OVERFLOW LINES DUE TO TEMPERTURE CHANGE AND MOTION OF VESSEL SMALL QUANTITY SPILLES ON DECK.  CLEANUP BY SHIP'S CREW, TANK INSPECTION BY TANK SURVEYOR AND APPROVED FOR CONTINUED CARRAGE TO DESTINATION.

column168: THE CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON RT.5 IN THE RIGHT OF SOUTHBOUND LANES. AN UNIDENTIFIED VEHICLE PULLED OUT DIRECTLY INTO THE PATH OF THE CARRIER'S VEHICLE.CARRIER'S DRIVER REACTED BY VEERING TO THE LEFT TO AVOID THIS CAR. THIS ABRUPT MOVE CAUSED THE REAR OF THE CARRIER'S VEHICLE TO YAW TO THE RIGHT. AS THE DRIVER CORRECTED, THE VEHICLE SLID LEFT,OVERTURNED AND SLID APPROXIMATELY 50 YARDS ON ITS LEFT SIDE RUBBING 3 HOLES IN THE SIDE OF THE TANK. THE VEHICLE THEN CONTINUED TO OVERTURN 1 COMPLETE TIME. THE IMPACT WITH THE PAVEMENT CAUSED THE FRONT LEFT CORNER OF THE BULKHEAD TO BUCKLE RUPTURING A HOLE. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE PARTIALLY ON THE HIGHWAY AND THE MEDIAN. THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF EXCESSIVE SPEED AND THE DRIVER HAD AND USED ALL OF THE APPROXIMATE 1 MILE SIGHT DISTANCE AVAILABLE AND DID NOT SEE THE CAR APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION UNTIL IT PULLED OUT INTO HIS PATH. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON DEFENSIVE MANEUVERS TO AVOID ACCIDENTS. ITEM #11: THE MARYLAND STATE POLICE, TRANSPORTATION INSPECTOR TOOK ALL OF OUR PAPERWORK FROM THE TRUCK. WE HAVE BEEN TRYING WITHOUT SUCCESS TO OBTAIN OUR SHIPPING PAPERS FROM THE DATE OF THE ACCIDENT. THIS REPORT WAS DELAYED TRYING TO GET THIS PAPERWORK.

SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT & FUTURE MEETING WITH SHIPPER ON SECUREMENT ISSUES SCHEDULED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) THROUGH THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV).  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND BOV HANDLE IN CLOSED POSITION. BOC TAPED WITH TEFLON STOPPING LEAK.  SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED. RESPONDERS ALSO NOTED THAT SOMEONE HAD SCRIBED 'BAD VALVE' TOWARD BOTTOM OF TANK CAR.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT, AS WELL AS, SUBSEQUENT RAIL CARRIER BY CHEMTREC.

ODOR REPORTED EMANATING FROM TANK CAR IN YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN & THE PLUG LOOSE.  VALVE CLOSED & PLUG TOOL TIGHTENED VAPOR LINE PLUG NOT APPLIED (NOT A SOURCE OF PRODUCT RELEASE) WAS APPLIED & TOOL TIGHTENED.  AFTER SECUREMENT ISSUES CORRECTED & NO ODOR PREVALENT, CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

ODOR REPORTED EMANATING FROM CAR STANDING IN YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAUGING DEVICE & NUT WAS TOOL TIGHTENED ELIMINATING ODOR.  LIQUID LINE SAMPLE VALVE PLUG LOOSE (NO PRODUCT RELEASE) & ALSO TOOL TIGHTENED.  AFTER SECUREMENT ISSUES CORRECTED & NO ODOR PREVALENT, TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORTED EXCESSIVE VENTING FROM TANK CONTAINER & CREW INSTRUCTED TO TAKE TRAIN TO NEEDLES, CA WHERE BNSF RESPONDERS WOULD MEET TRAIN.  AT NEEDLES, RESPONDERS FOUND THE V-10 LIQUID LINE SAMPLE VALVE HAD CREPT OPEN.  VALVE CLOSED & TIED TO ELIMINATE FUTURE VIBRATION OPENING.  TANK CONTAINER & TRAIN RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER REPAIRS COMPLETED.  TOTAL TRAIN DELAY WAS 1 HOUR 35 MINUTES AT PICA & 15 MINUTES AT NEEDLES.  FOUR OTHER PRIORITY TRAINS DELAYED.

INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT VAPOR EMANATING FROM CAR & APPROX 50 BNSF PERSONNEL WERE WITHDRAWN FROM IMMEDIATE AREA.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND PRODUCT VAPOR BY PASSING THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, MOST LIKELY DEFECTIVE.  CAR DEPRESSURIZED BY 1105 CDST & VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED; CAR & TRAIN RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTERWARDS. SHIPPER NOTIFIED TO REPAIR OR REPLACE THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE PRIOR TO RELOADING THIS CAR.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW NOTICED TANK CAR VENTING EXCESSIVELY & SET CAR OUT IN YARD TRACK OFF MAINLINE.  BNSF & SHIPPER RESPONDERS FOUND PRODUCT RELEASING THROUGH LIQUID LINE DUE TO LIQUID LINE PACKING NUT OFF STEM & VALVE CREPT OPEN.  RESPONDERS CLOSED VALVE & TIGHTENED PACKING NUT STOPPING PRODUCT RELEASE.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER REPAIRS COMPLETED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS MAKING ROUTINE YARD CHECK, NOTICED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM CAR.  RESPONDERS FOUND ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS FINGER LOOSE.  PRESSURE REDUCED FROM CAR & BOLT TOOL TIGHTENED.  AFTER ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS RECHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS & NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR DEFECTED, CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AT 2300 MDST.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT FOR THEIR FOLLOW-UP INVESTIGATION OF THIS SECUREMENT ISSUE.

OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED LIQUID PRODUCT SEEPING FROM TOP OF CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THAT THE UNLOADING CONNECTION SCREW VALVE WAS TWO TURNS LOOSE ON ITS PIPE NIPPLE.  CONNECTION WAS WRENCH TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING RELEASE.  RESPONDERS WIPED OFF RESIDUE OF SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK SHELL.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT AND IS DEVELOPING PROGRAMS TO ELIMINATE FUTURE REOCCURRENCES.

HRRX 126 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES.  REACT ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE THERMOMETER WELL TUBE HAD CORRODED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ENTER THE TUBE AND ESCAPE TO ATMOSPHERE AROUND THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP.  A MIDLAND CAPPING KIT WAS APPLIED TO CONTROL THE LEAK UNTIL THE CAR'S CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED FOR DELIVERY.  THE CAR WILL BE MOVED TO A TANK CAR REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS AFTER CLEANING AND PURGING.

UTLX 49864 NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT VAPOR IN AREA OF CAR.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, REACT ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE JACKET AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR INDICATING THE INNER LINER AND TANK SHELL HAD BEEN BREACHED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSFERRED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT TO TANK TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY.  THE EMPTY CAR WAS PURGED AND TRANSPORTED TO A TANK CAR REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND CONTAINMENT BALLAST WAS PROPERLY COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OR NEUTRALIZED ON SIGHT.

APHX 2011 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND CARRIER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED.  CARRIER AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK FROM THE PACKING NUT AND OPERATING STEM OF THE VAPOR LINE VALVE.  A SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE REVEALED EVIDENCE THAT THE VALVE HAD RECENTLY FUNCTIONED.  THIS OBSERVATION WAS VALIDATED BY THE FACT THAT THE PRESSURE GAUGES ON THE CAR INDICATED THE PRESSURE WAS RISING ABOUT 2.5 PSI PER HOUR.  AFTER IMPLEMENTING PROPER SAFETY PRECAUTIONS THE VAPORS INSIDE THE CAR WERE FLARED-OFF TO REDUCE AND STABILIZE THE PRESSURE INSIDE THE CAR.  AFTER CONSULTATION WITH THE SHIPPER AND EMERGENCY RESPONDERS THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSPORT THE CAR TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING.  THE CAR WAS CLOSELY MONITORED ENROUTE AND ARRIVED DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF TRAILER#8531, OUR PROCESSING PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED A RELEASE OF SOLID MATERIALS FROM A PLASTIC DRUM THAT FELL ON ITS SIDE. THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED UPRIGHT AND THE SOLIDS WERE PICKED UP. THE SOLIDS THAT WERE RELEASED WERE LOCATED OUTSIDE OF RED INNER LINER. THE AREA, ON WHICH THE RELEASE OCCURRED, WAS DECONTAMINATED. AS A MEANS OF PREVENTING A RECURRENCE, WE WILL ENSURE THAT SHIPMENTS ARE PROPERLY BRACED, AND WE WILL REVIEW THE REQUIRED PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS WITH THE SHIPPER (GENERATOR/CUSTOMER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: TWO IDENTICAL CONTAINERS WERE SITTING ON WOODEN PALLETS ON THE SAN MARTIN PAD TO BE LOADED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DISPOSAL SITE. ON 10-16-00 @ APPROX 0830 HRS. PAD PERSONNEL PEDRO DEL REAL AND VICTOR LOPEZ OPENING UP THE PAD OBSERVED THE FRONT CONTAINER HAD BEEN LEAKING. APPROX 1 1/2 QTS OF LIQUID HAD COME OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE WOODEN PALLET AND ASPHALT PAD, THE PALLET OF THE 2 ND CONTAINER WAS ALSO CONTAMINATED. PEDRO CONTACTED RICHARD SALAZAR AND DAN HENDRICKS WHO RESPONDED TO THE PAD AND ACCESSED THE SITUATION. ABSORPTION SWEEP WAS PUT ON THE LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED OUT AND AROUND THE LEAKING CONTAINER. BOTH CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO PLASTIC BINS ALONG WITH THE CLEAN  UP MATERIALS THEN SHRINK WRAPPED PLASTIC WAS PUT AROUND THEM FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL.
NO REMARKS
column172: Plastic liner for fiber drums and boxes or metal drums containing liquids

column168: DRIVER WAS STARTING TO BEGIN UNLOADING PRODUCT THROUGH A 2" HOSE, HE HEARD UNLOADING PUMP LABOR AND BEFORE HE COULD SHUT DOWN SYSTEM ON TRUCK THE UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED APPROXIMATELY 5" FROM THE END WHERE COUPLING ATTACHED TO CUSTOMERS INLET LINE.  THERE APPARENTLY WAS A VALVE PARTIALLY CLOSED IN THE SYSTEM WHICH CREATED THE BACK PRESSURE WHICH CAUSED THE HOSE TO RUPTURE.  APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON UNLOADING PAD AND CLEANED UP BY THE RECEIVER.
I WAS CALLED TO THE BELT AT DOOR 35 FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE IN WHICH I RESPONDED ACCORDING TO THE DECISION TREE.

THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER'S SPILL CLEANUP GROUP.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD IN A SECURE AREA UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION HAS BEEN RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILL CLEANUP WAS DONE PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICY.

column168: PACKAGE DISCOVERED WITH SMALL LEAKAGE AT DESTINATION STATION.  SPILL CONTAINED INSIDE PACKAGE AND NO OTHER PACKAGES INVOLVED. RECEIVED 5 DIFFERENT MSDS'S FOR SHIPMENT AND THREE OF THEM INDICATED FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THEY ARE IDENTIFIED AS INK, ONE WITH A FLASH POINT OF 135 DEGREES F, ONE WITH 101 DEGREES F. APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS 10-06-00 TRAIN CREW NOTICED LIQUID LEAK FROM TOP OF RAIL CAR GATX 79745 WHICH CONTAINED MTBE ENROUTE TO KERN OIL COMPANY.  CAR WAS LOCATED IN SJVR'S BAKERSFIELD YARD.  SJVR SAFETY OFFICER, PAUL GOINS AND THE KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT TEAM MET AT THE SCENE, TOGETHER WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF KERN OIL REFINING.  INSPECTION DEYEWOPED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM 3" FLANGE GASKET ON TOP INLET VALVE.  REPAIRS MADE ON SITE BY TIGHTENING BOLTS.  CAR THEN MOVED TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING. INFORMATION FURNISHED TO SHIPPER TO HELP ENSURE NO RECURRENCE.

PACKAGE OBSERVED LEAKING DURING SORT OPERATION, BOTTOM OF PACKAGE WET.  DUE TO NATURE OF CONTENTS, PACKAGE IMMEDIATELY PLACED INTO STEEL SALVAGE DRUM WITHOUT FURTHER INVESTIGATION, SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.
PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING, DUE TO LOOSE CLOSURE.  PACKAGE PLACED INTO STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT/RELOAD WHEN THE LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THE CAP SEAL ON THE JERRICAN HAD APPARENTLY FAILED.  THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF SOME OF THE MATERIAL FROM ITS INITIAL PACKAGING.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE LEAKING UNIT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT ORIGIN.
THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES OCCURRED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A FEDEX SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A FEDEX SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVEPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LA GRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KY FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. column168: A CSXT CAR INSPECTOR WAS CHECKING INBOUND TRAIN, Q64009 AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN NEW CASTLE, PA.  HE DISCOVERED WETNESS ON ONE SIDE OF T/C ACFX 200533, LD ENVIRONMENTALY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, NOS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED RESCAR TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  RESCAR FOUND TWO (2) OF THE 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  THEY TIGHTENED THE LOOSE BOLTS AND CHECKED THE REMAINING MANWAY BOLTS.  RESCAR CLEANED OFF THE RESIDUE ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND IT RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: DURING A YARD INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN CUMBERLAND, MD.  AAR INSPECTOR, BILL OERTLY FOUND A VERY SLIGHT LEAK, DETECTED ONLY BY CLOSE OBSERVATION, ON THE NOZZLE ON T/C UTLX 75022, LOAD OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO CUMBERLAND AND FOUND TWO (2) MANWAY BOLTS LOOSE.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED AND PRODUCT RESIDUE WAS WIPED OFF OF NOZZLE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON OCTOBER 13, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN GREENWICH YARD IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, NOTICED SUNX 90013 VENTING VAPORS ONTO THE RAILS FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTORS AND CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED.  A THREE-WAY VALVE TO A 3/8" BLEEDER WAS FOUND IN THE OPEN POSITION. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE RELEASE STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

A YARD CREW WORKING THE CLASSIFICATION YARD AT CSXTS RAIL YARD IN LOUISVILLE, KY, OBSERVED WETNESS ON THE SIDE OF ACFX 79304, LOAD OF TOLUENE.  THE TERMINAL TRAINMASTER ISOLATED THE CAR.  THE CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CONTINUOUS AND COMING FROM THE 2" BALL VALVE ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  THE BALL VALVE WAS LEAKING AT THE JOINT BETWEEN THE UPPER AND LOWER SECTIONS OF THE VALVE.  THE CAR WAS DEPRESSURIZED AND THE VALVE REPAIRED.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON OCTOBER 16, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE ATLANTA YARD FOUND GATX 24689, A LOADED TANK CAR OF FUEL OIL, LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY WHEN MOVED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED A CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET CUT.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, THE MANWAY WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON OCTOBER 16, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM ACFX 83765, A LOADED TANK CAR OF CRUDE SULFITE TURPENTINE, IN THE CSXT GRAND RAPIDS YARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED THAT CSXT PROVIDE RESPONSE THOUGH A CSXT CONTRACTOR.  A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND FOUND TWO MANWAY BOLTS LOOSE AND HANGING. THE OTHER SIX MANWAY BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE PLUGS IN THE LIQUID, VAPOR AND SAMPLE LINES WERE ALSO LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED ALL PLUGS AND BOLTS, THE ODOR ABATED, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

ETCX 630554, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ACETALDEHYDE, WAS DETECTED TO HAVE A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK, REPORTED BY A CARMAN WHO NOTICED THE ODOR AT CSXTS RAIL YARD IN PLAINFIELD, IN.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED AND ISOLATED FOR REPAIR.  TWO RAILROAD PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE "B" END PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAD SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK.  THE NUT ON THE "O" RING RETAINING CAP WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  CAR WILL BE SHIPPED TO DESTINATION.  DESTINATION HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE REPAIR IN ORDER TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION UPON ARRIVAL AT FACILITY.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO FIND ONE 3-GALLON CAN OF A 4 CAN SHIPMENT SEEPING.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRUM WAS PUSHED AGAINST A PROTRUDING SCREW, WHICH CAUSED A PINHOLE IN THE BOTTOM EDGE OF THE CAN.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP WITH CHEMICAL TOWELS AND THESE TOWELS AND THE DRUM WERE OVERPACKED AND ARE STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.

column26: UNIT E FRT FWDG BLDG BELFAST A
column168: A FORKLIFT PUNCTURED A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 4-5 LITER CONTAINERS OF PROVITA HOOFSURE MADE IN N. IRELAND.  THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED ONE 5-LITER PLASTIC CONTAINER WHICH LEAKED ONTO FLOOR. ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CONTAIN LIQUID.  THE PRODUCT CONTAINED FORMIC ACID (47%) AND ACETIC ACID (11%) EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WAS CALLED TO CLEAN SPILL AND DISPOSE OF LEAKED PRODUCT.

ON 10/11/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 0750 HOURS, WHILE INSPECTING RAILCARS IN THE GEISMAR YARD, A CN/IC CARMAN DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 27955 (AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS).  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED, NOTING A LEAK FROM THE -A- END LIQUID VALVE END PLUG.  PIPE WRENCH USED TO PROPERLY SECURE VALVE AND END PLUG, LEAK STOPPED.  TANK CAR THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

ON 10/06/00 RAILCAR #ACFX-94234 CONTAINING STYRENE MONOMER WAS SAMPLED TO VERIFY THE DISPOSITION OF IT'S CONTENTS.  THE SAMPLE INDICATED THAT THE STYRENE WAS BEGINNING TO POLYMERIZE.  THE MANUFACTURER WAS CONTACTED AND A REQUEST FOR TECHNICAL ADVICE WAS MADE BY ATOFINA CHEMICALS, INC.  THE MANUFACTURER RECOMMENDED TRANSFERRING THE CONTENTS OF THE RAILCAR INTO CARGO TANKS AND ADDING INHIBITOR TO STABILIZE THE POLYMERIZATION.  THIS PLAN WAS EXPECTED TO BE CARRIED OUT EARLY MORNING ON 10/07/00.  TEMPERATURE MONITORING OF THE RAILCAR LATER THAT NIGHT (10/06) INDICATED INCREASING TEMPERATURE OF THE STYRENE THEREFORE THE COMPANY WAS UNABLE TO CARRY OUT THIS PLAN.  THE RAILCAR WAS MOVED TO A REMOTE AREA AND THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSENED TO PREVENT PRESSURE BUILD UP THAT COULD LEAD TO POSSIBLE RUPTURE OF THE RAILCAR.  AT 23:40 HRS. THE RAILCAR BEGAN TO VENT FROM THE MANWAY, THE VENTING CONTINUED UNTIL MID MORNING ON 10/07/00 AND THEN STOPPED.  AN ESTIMATED 9,200 POUND RELEASE OF STYRENE VAPORS HAS BEEN ESTIMATED.  SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE MANWAY POLYMERIZED AND WAS CONTAINED AT THE RAILCAR.  THESE SEQUENCES OF EVENTS ALL OCCURRED ON OUR PLANT SITE AND THE CLEAN UP OF POLYMERIZED MATERIAL WILL BEGIN AS SOON AS THE RAILCAR'S CONTENTS HAS COOLED TO AN ACCEPTABLE LEVEL.  THIS INCIDENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE AND THE ACTIONS REQUIRED TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.

BOOTS AND COOTS HAD ONE EMPLOYEE WHO STEPPED ON A NAIL INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THE NAIL PIERCED THE BOTTOM OF HIS FOOT.  HE WAS WEARING STEEL TOED SAFETY BOOTS.  THE NAIL WAS IN THE FLOOR ON THE CONTAINER.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: ACFX 87914, LD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS, WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY CAR INSPECTOR DURING INBOUND INSPECTION OF TRAIN AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SELKIRK, NY.  YARD SUPERVISION WAS NOTIFIED AND TRAIN MOVEMENT ON SURROUNDING TRACKS WAS HALTED.  CSXTS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED AND HE CALLED THE SHIPPER.  THE TANK CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE OPERATING ROD OF OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE ONE FULL TURN.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED AND PRODUCT COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CAP WAS SECURED AND THE CAR MONITORED FOR LEAKAGE BEFORE IT WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS DISCUSSED WITH SHIPPER.

UTLX 200120 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, OIL MOP, INC., RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS STOPPING THE RELEASE.

GATX 17854 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR ON TOP OF CAR BY CARRIER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL DURING HAZMAT YARD INSPECTION. CARRIER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED 8 OF 8 LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS SHOPPING THE RELEASE.

GATX 11816 NOTED WITH PRODUCT SPLASHING FROM THE TOP OF CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, REACT ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISC STOPPING THE RELEASE.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT THE DISC HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY INSTALLED AND SHOWED SIGNS OF CORROSION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2230 HOURS/ 21OCTOO A FORKLIFT OPERATOR ENGAGED IN THE OFFLOADING OF FLIGHT SR 104 PUNCTURED 2 DRUMS OF THE AFOREMENTIONED SHIPMENT. THE DG CERTIFICATE WAS CHECKED AND THE 2000 EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOKLET WAS CHECKED & INSTRUCTIONS FOLLOWED. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED. SUPERVISOR REPORT INDICATES HE SPOKE WITH "JOHN LONG" OF CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED TO APPLY "AN ABSORBENT" AND VENTILATE THE AREA. THESE ACTIONS WERE TAKEN CHEMTERC CHECKED THEIR LISTING OF THE "MSDS" AND ADVISED NO TOXICITY THREAT. BOTH CSC & CHEMNTREC ATTEMPTED ON CONTACTING THE CONSIGNEE IN NEWJERSEY HOWEVER THERE WS NO ANSWER TO THE PHONE. THE "24 HOUR EMERGENCY" PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE DG CERTIFICATE WAS A GERMAN NUMBER AND CONTACT WAS NOT MADE. THE ULD WAS STILL INTACT AND EFFORTS TO QUICKLY CONTAIN THE SPILL WERE MADE. THE ENTIRE UNIT WAS PLACED OUTDOORS TO VENTILATE. PANYNJ POLICE WERE NOT NOTIFIED. ON THE AFTERNOON OF OCT 22ND, SEVERAL STAFF COMPLAINED OF NAUSEA & WERE SENT TO THE MEDICAL CLINIC, SHORTLY THEREAFTER PANYNJ POLICE CALLED & ARRIVED AT BLDG 151. AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS PANYNJ POLICE CLOSED THE FACILITY. THE VARIOUS MEMBERS OF CSC MANAGEMENT WERE CALLED AND ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AT VARIOUS TIMES. THE 24 HOUR EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE DG CERTIFICATE IN GERMANY WAS CALLED, HOWEVER THERE WAS NO ANSWER. A FOLLOW-UP TELEX REQUESTING A TOXICITY STATEMENT ("MSDS") WAS REQUESTED FROM FRA. PANYNJ HAZMAT SPECIALIST ASSESSED & AFFECTED A CLEAN-UP OF THE AREA AND THE FACILITY WAS RE-OPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 HOURS. CSC CONTACTED & CONTRACTED THE HAZMAT CLEAN-UP SERVICES OF H.M.H.T.T.C. WHO ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2045 HOURS. THEREAFTER THEY APPLY ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT, SWEPT, VACUUMED & CONTAINED ALL INTERIOR & EXTERIOR RESIDUE. A TOTAL OF 12 CSC STAFF MEMBERS SOUGHT MEDICAL ATTENTION AT KENNEDY MEDICAL CENTER AND AN UNKNOWN NUMBER OF POSSIBLE OTHER SUB-CONTRACTED STAFF. ALL 12 CSC MEMBERS WERE RELEASED & DEEMED FIT TO RETURN TO NORMAL DUTY. CSC'S INSURANCE CO. WAS INFORMED OF THE DETAILS AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, OCT 23RD. INFORMATION VIA SEPARATE REPORT.

THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO SECURED THE CLOSURES ON THE CAR. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT THE TIME.

ON OCT 21, 2000 TANK CAR GATX 45065, LOAD OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS FOUND TO LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED IN TRANSPORTATION.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER CALLED.  SHIPPER, ASHTA CHEMICALS ADVISED THAT OXY CHEM. ASHTABULA, OH. DID THE LOADING OF THE CAR AND WOULD SEND RESCAR TO DO REPAIRS.  RESCAR RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE 165# RUPTURE DISC.  CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVING ON TO DESTINATION.

ON OCT. 22, 2000 TANK CAR GATX 18834, LOAD OF HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE SOLUTION WAS FOUND TO LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN CAR SITTING IN THE GREENWOOD, S.C. YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER CALLED.  SHIPPER HAD CONSIGNEE RESPOND.  CONSIGNEE RESPONDED IN THE EVENING HOURS AND FOUND THE CAR HAD BEEN OVERLOADED AND HAD VENTED THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  CAR WAS VENTED ABLING THE CAR TO BE MOVED INTO INDUSTRY FOR OFF LOADING.

ON OCTOBER 30, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT LEEWOOD YARD IN MEMPHIS, TN, FOUND DBCX 620, A LOADED TANK CAR OF 2-ETHYL HEXANOL, LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  YARD PERSONNEL PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND ISOLATED THE AREA. M.D. LUNSFORD, CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SYSTEMS, RESPONDED TO THE LEAK.  THE LIQUID VALVE HANDLE WAS FOUND REMOVED AND THE OUTSIDE NUT REMOVED.  THE INSIDE (PACKING) NUT WAS LOOSE AND PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE PACKING.  THE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED, THE OUTSIDE NUT WAS APPLIED AND TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.  A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SITE TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED BALLAST.

ON OCT. 30, 2000 TANK CAR, GATX 11468, LD. OF CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET OPERATING ROD AND PACKING GLAND, BY OHIO PUCO INSPECTOR K. HEDGLIN. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA.  CHEMTREC.  SHIPPER RESPONDED RESCAR FROM TOLEDO, OH.  WHO FOUND THE PACKING GLAND NUT LOOSE ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ROD. CAR WAS SECURED BY TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: DRIVER NOTICED S03 FUMES LEAKING OUT OF DOME OF TRAILER.  BELLE TERP TEAM RESPONDED, SEALED THE DOME AND PACKED THE AREA WITH SODA ASH. THE TRAILER WAS THEN TAKEN TO BELLE PLANT.  THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD AFTER TRAILER REPAIRS.  THE LEAK IS CURRENTLY BE INVESTIGATED.

A TRAILER WAS DOCKED AT A TRANSFER STATION AND WAS LOADED WITH WASTE THAT WAS REJECTED BY THE SAFETY-KLEEN DISPOSAL FACILITY IN SMITHFIELD, KY AND WAS BEING SENT BACK TO THE GENERATOR.  THE MATERIAL WAS BEING UNLOADED AND PUT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER GOING TO THE GENERATOR'S SITE.  THEY FOUND A PALLET OF FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS HAD TIPPED OVER AND TWO OF THE CONTAINERS HAD BEEN DAMAGED.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS SPILLED A TOTAL OF THREE GALLONS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE OTHER DRUMS REPALLETIZED . THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE GENERATOR AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY IN PECATONICA, IL.

THE DRIVER WAS IN TRANSIT GOING FROM ONE CUSTOMER SITE TO ANOTHER. DUE TO THE STEEP GRADE AT A CUSTOMER SITE, A FIVE GALLON POLY DRUM TIPPED OVER AND THE LID POPPED OFF SPILLING FOUR GALLONS OF PHOTO FIXER SOLUTION INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 35 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE STREET IN CANTON,  MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOAD SECUREMENT AND DRUM CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A FORKLIFT DRIVER AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY WAS MOVING A PALLET OF WASTE IN THE WAREHOUSE WHEN A 55 GALLON DRUM FELL OFF SPILLING 50 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID.  THE SPILL OCCURRED IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM AND WASTE ABSORBENT WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 1,320 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 500 BATTLEGROUND ROAD IN LA PORTE, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUES AND DRUM HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, UNLOADER FOUND THIS DRUM IN TRAILER WITH A LITTLE WET SPOT ALONG SIDE OF IT.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE TOP CHIME.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

WHILE LOADING DRUM INTO TRAILER, DOCKWORKER SAID DRUM JUST FELL APART.  THE MATERIAL INSIDE OF THE DRUM WAS A SOLID MATERIAL AND IT FELL APART WHERE THE LEVEL OF MATERIAL WAS LOCATED.  THE DRUM ITSELF LOOKED WORN AND CORRODED WITH AGE.  THE MATERIAL INSIDE OF IT WAS A SOLID MASS, SO THE AMOUNT THAT SPILLED WAS RECOVERED EASILY.  PUT FATIGUED DRUM AND PRODUCT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE TEMPORARILY STAGED ON PLATFORM, A DOCKWORKER NOTICED THIS IBC HAD A SMALL PUDDLE UNDERNEATH OF IT BY THE VALVE ASSEMBLE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS FOUND TO BE SLIGHTLY LEAKING FROM A THREADED NIPPLE WHERE THE VALVE ASSEMBLY IS MOUNTED. WE  TOOK A BRASS WRENCH AND TIGHTENED THE NIPPLE WHICH STOPPED 98 PERCENT OF THE LEAK.  WE THEN TOOK SOME LEAK PUTTY AND APPLIED IT TO THE THREADED AREA WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK COMPLETELY.  AFTER THE PUTTY CURED AND IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS NOT LEAKING ANYMORE, WE RETURNED IT TO THE SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DRUMS AT CONSIGNEE.  WHEN HE TIPPED THE DRUM BACK IT WAS OBSERVED THAT IT STARTED LEAKING SOMEWHERE DOWN AT THE BOTTOM.  WHEN THE DRUM WAS STOOD BACK UP IT WOULD STOP LEAKING.  TRIED TIPPING IT AGAIN, STARTED LEAKING AGAIN.  STOOD IT BACK UP - IT STOPPED!!  APPARENTLY THERE WAS A SMALL CRACK IN THE DRUM, HOWEVER NOT SURE WHAT ACTION CONTRIBUTED TO THIS FAILURE.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE, WET CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING ONE, FIVE GALLON BLADDER OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGING. column168: FILE:  3027 D, DATE:  10/27/2000, SHIPPER:  MONARCH INDUSTRIES, INC., AWB # PVD 882055864 AAA.  ON 10/27/2000 AT 0115 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS PAUL SCHMIDT AND CECILLE HICKEY DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS BELIEVED TO EMITTING THE ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THIS SHIPMENT FROM THE AREA, AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION.  UPON THIS INSPECTION THEY FOUND 1 X 3.7854 L METAL RECEPTACLE WITH A PLASTIC SEAL ON LID.  THIS WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES FROM UNDER THE PLASTIC SEAL.  THIS WAS PACKED INSIDE OF A PLASTIC BAG WHICH WAS TIED IN A KNOT.  THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEM BACK INTO BOX, RESEALED IT, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED IT ONTO IT'S DESTINATION. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES IN THIS EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  THERE ARE PICTURES OF THIS SHIPMENT ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0182.

NINE OF THE DRUMS WERE DAMAGED AND THERE WAS MINOR LEAKAGE FROM ONE DRUM.  THE VEHICLE WAS NOT CONTAMINATED AND THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD AT OUR WAREHOUSE AT 3600 W CENTURY BLVD, INGLEWOOD, CA.  IT WILL BE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE 50 POUND BAG OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DAMAGED IN THE TRAILER.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA WAS HIRED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. RECOVERED THE ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT THAT RELEASED INTO PLASTIC RECOVERY BAGS.  THE RECOVERY BAGS WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  CLEANUP IS COMPLETE.

column168: DRIVER MAKING DELIVERY AND OVERFLOWED UST.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE PAVEMENT AND STORM SEWER.  NO SOIL WAS CONTAMINATED.  A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ENTERED THE STORM SEWER WHICH WAS FLUSHED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ER TEAM.  A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST WITH REMEDIATION.  RESIDENTS ACROSS STREET WERE NOT HOME AT TIME OF SPILL BUT DID ATTEMPT TO RETURN DURING CLEANUP PROCESS AND WAS DELAYED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ALL REGULATOR AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

A DRUM WAS AT TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY BEING UNLOADED FROM A TRUCK USING A FORKLIFT. WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED THE LID POPPED OFF DUE TO AN IMPROPERLY TIGHTENED BOLT AND TWO GALLONS OF COMBUSTIBLE OIL SPILLED OUT ONTO THE FLOOR. THE SPILL HAPPENED IN THE WAREHOUSE'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED. THE LID AND RING WAS REPLACED ON THE 55 GALLON DRUM WITH BOLT PROPERLY TIGHTENED. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED. ONE INNER BOTTLE WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE CAP. THE BOX AND ALL BOTTLES WERE RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE LOADING, ONE 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 55 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS, TWO 55 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUMS AND ONE 80 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL FIVE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND PLACED INTO AN 80-GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 3/4 MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND DRIED ONTO THE PAIL.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, DAMAGED PAIL, AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A SIX GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE IS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE VALVE ON TOP OF THE TOTE.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED TOTE WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING REPAIR BY THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: ON OCTOBER 31, 2000, A DRUM OF A SULFURIC ACID MIXTURE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING INSIDE OF A TRANSPORT VAN AT APPROXIMATELY 17:30 CST. THE DRIVER OF THE TRANSPORT UNIT DIKED THE LEAKING MATERIAL WITH DIRT AND CALLED HIS DISPATCH OFFICE WHO IN TURN CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC.  (EMI) WHO THEN INITIATED A RESPONSE. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING CAUSTIC LIME AND LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED AND SHIPPED ON TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.

THE DRIVER WAS AT A CUSTOMER'S SITE TO PICK-UP A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE TOLUENE.  THE DRUM WAS NOT SUITABLE FOR TRANSPORTATION AND NEEDED TO BE OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  IN THE PROCESS OF OVERPACKING THE DRUM, FIVE GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE CONCRETE PAD WHERE THEY WERE OVERPACKING THE DRUM. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM ALSO.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 55 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

AT 1700, EMERY WORLDWIDE PICKED UP 2 BOXES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FROM AIRSTECH IN FLORENCE KY. THE 2 BOXES WERE LOADED ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE REAR END OF THE CARGO BOX ON THE VEHICLE. AT 1850, THE VEHICLE WAS MAKING A PICK UP AT THE MAZAK CORPORATION WHEN THE MAZAK FORKLIFT OPERATOR BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND RAN OVER THE 2 BOXES OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE EMERY WORLDWIDE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PHONED THE OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR AT THE CVG EMERY SERVICE CENTER. THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER, AND WAS ADVISED ON THE STEPS NEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. EMERY IS EVALUATING DISPOSAL OPTIONS WITH ARISTECH.

column168: ON 25 OCTOBER 2000 FLAT CAR#CP 521173 ENTERED THE CONKOLIN STREET YARD IN BINGHAMTON NEW YORK. DURING THAT DAY IT WAS NOTED THAT A THICK LIQUID MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM CONTAINER ENAU 2450176.  THE CONTAINER WAS MARKED AS CLASS 3 ALSO WITH MARINE HAZARD MARKINGS.  THE LEAK WAS NOTED WHEN THE CAR WAS ON TRACK # 5.  THE FLAT CAR WAS ISOLATED TO TRACK # 17 NORTH.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR BY CP RAIL YARD STAFF,  AFTER OP-TECH STAFF INSURED THAT THE LEVELS AROUND THE CONTAINER DID NOT PRESENT A HAZARD TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR WORKING STAFF.  THE CONTAINER (ENAU 2450176) WAS REMOVED AND PLACED ON POLY SHEETING WITH CONTAINMENT BOOM.  THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED FOR THE EVENING AND A FIR- WATCH POSTED. ON 26 OCTOBER 2000 OP-TECH STAFF PREPARED TO OPEN THE CONTAINED. THE LEL LEVELS OUTSIDE THE CONTAINER WERE 0 % AND PID LEVELS WERE LESS THAN 10 PPM. THE CONTAINER WAS THAN OPENED WHILE TAKING CONTINUES READINGS THE LEVELS OBTAINED WERE LEL 0% AND PID LESS THAN 10PPM WITH THE LEAKING MATERIAL MEASURING A PH OF 3.5 SU.  WITH THE CONTAINER OPEN IT WAS NOTED THAT THE INTERIOR CONTAINED 55 GAL DRUMS LABELED GRAPEFRUIT OIL, TERPRENE HYDROCARBONS, NOS (TERPENES) CLASS 3 3, UN 2319, PG III.  THERE WAS NOT EVIDENCE THAT BLOCKING WAS USED IN THE LOADING OF THE CONTAINER, THERE WAS  STRONG "CITRUS" ODOR BUT NO VISIBLE LEAKAGE.  USING LEVEL C PPE OP-TECH STAFF UNPACKED THE CONTAINER.  ONE LEAKING CONTAINER (CONTAINED LESS THAN 1 GAL WHEN FOUND) WAS LOCATED IN THE CONTAINER IN THE THIRD ROW RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS WAS THE ONLY LEAKING DRUM FOUND.

column168: WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED AT HIS FIRST STOP, THE DRIVER AND THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVER FOUND BROWN LIQUID RUNNING OUT THE TRAILER. THE RECEIVER REQUESTED THAT THE DRIVER TO LEAVE THE DOCK DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR ACCOMPANYING THE SPILLAGE. DRIVER WENT TO THE EDGE OF THE PROPERTY AND NOTIFIED THE CARRIER VIA HIS CELL PHONE. THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. EMPLOYEES OF THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE AN HOUR LATER. THEY INSPECTED THE LOAD AND FOUND A DRUM OF PRINTING INK FOR A SUBSEQUENT STOP THAT HAD FALLEN OFF OF ITS PALLET. THE DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM AS A RESULT. SEVERAL DRUMS AND PAILS FROM OTHER SHIPMENTS HAD WORKED LOOSE BUT NO OTHERS FAILED. THE CONTRACTOR REWORKED THE LOAD IN ORDER TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE SPILL. AFTER CLEANING UP THE SPILL AND ALL OF THE FREIGHT, THEY RESECURED THE LOAD. ALL SHIPMENTS WERE THEN DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

THE PALLET WAS UNLOADED FROM THE TRAILER, THE DAMAGED BAGS REMOVED AND THE REMAINING BAGS RESTACKED. THE DAMAGED BAGS WERE HELD AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

SOME OTHER BAGS IN THE MIDDLE OF THE PALLET WERE TORN ON THE OUTER WALL BUT WERE NOT LEAKING. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED ALL WITH A NOTATION. THEY SWEPT OUT THE TRAILER FLOOR AND DISPOSED OF THE WASTE. SHIPMENT WAS ORIGINALLY 141 BAGS BUT TWO WERE HELD OFF AT THE CARRIER'S OUTBOUND FACILITY AS THEY HAD ARRIVED FROM THE  SHIPPER WITH DAMAGE VISIBLE.

WHEN THE CONSIGNEE'S FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS REMOVING A PALLET OF DRUMS, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THERE IS A SMALL SLIT AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, WHICH LOOKS TO HAVE BEEN HIT BY A FORK. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE AT THE PREVIOUS STOP WHICH IS 50 MILES AWAY. THE CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED THE RHINELANDER FIRE DEPT. HAZMAT TEAM. THEY ARRIVED AND CLEANED THE SPILL WITH SPEEDY DRY, AND THEN WASHED THE TRAILER DOWN. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS LEFT AT THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: AN UNLOADER NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE. A 12 HOUR RESPONDER WAS SUMMONED AND ACCESS TO AREA WAS RESTRICTED.  THE PACKAGE HAD A DIAMOND CORROSIVE LABEL. THE LIQUID HAD A PH OF 2. THE SPILL WAS THEN SOLIDIFIED USING CLAY ABSORBANT AND ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH UPS DMP PROCEDURES.

LEFT HUB WITH JERSEY CITY CENTER SUPV. (BILL) GOING TO BAYONNE,  NJ TO CAVEHEM INC. 40 AVE A, WHEN WE GOT TO BUILDING THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THEM PEOPLE, BROUGHT BACK TO HUB TO GENERATE AND SENT TO DMP FOR DISPOSAL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1040 MILITARY TIME ON OCTOBER 30, 2000, OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A #2 FUEL OIL DELIVERY TO THE PREMISES OF 1132 BEACH AVENUE BRONX NEW YORK.  WHILE ENGAGING IN THE DELIVERY THE DECK HOSE BETWEEN THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER RUPTURED SPRAYING OIL INTO THE STREET AT A FAST PACE.  ALL EQUIPMENT IS CHECKED BEFORE LEAVING FOR A ROUTE, BUT LIKE A BLOW OUT OF A TIRE, IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO FORESEE A HOSE GIVING WAY, WHEN VISIBLY NO DEFECTS ARE DETECTED.  THE DRIVER MANAGED TO DISENGAGE THE PUMP TO STOP THE FLOW OF OIL.  WE IMMEDIATELY SENT A CLEAN UP CREW AND RECEIVED A DEC SPILL # 8820.  WE SATISFIED THE LOCAL POLICE, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DEP & DEC AUTHORITIES WITH OUR CLEAN UP RESPONSE AND PROCEDURES.  IN THE FUTURE WE INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS TO PRACTICE SHUT DOWN OF PUMP PROCEDURES IN CASE THIS UNEXPECTED ACT OF NATURE EVER OCCURS AGAIN.

column168: AT APPROX 1205 HRS ON OCT 22 2000 A FIRE OCCURRED AS A TANKER TRANSPORT TRUCK WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS AT THE MARTIN GAS FILL STATION.  THE PRODUCT TRANSFER LINES HAD BEEN CONNECTED BETWEEN THE TRANSPORT AND THE STATIONARY EQUIPMENT AS THE FILL STATION BY THE UNLOADER AND OFF LOADING WAS PROGRESSING WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AFTER ABOUT FIVE MINUTES OF PUMPING AND AS THE DRIVER WAS WALKING WITHOUT INCIDENT. AFTER ABOUT 5 MINUTES OF PUMPING ND AS THE DRIVER WAS WALKING AWAY FROM THE TRANSPORT, HE HEARD A POP, TURNED TO SEE AND EXPANDING VAPOR CLOUD AND HEARD THE TRACTOR ENGINE SPEED UP.  HE RETURNED TO THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK TRACTOR JUST AS THE HYDROCARBON IGNITED.  THE UNLOADER WAS UNABLE TO ESCAPE THE ENSUING FIRE, WHICH WAS CENTER AROUND THE MID SECTION OF THE TANKER TRANSPORT IN THE VICINITY OF THE TRANSFER PUMP AND VALVE MANIFOLD ARRANGEMENT ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANKER.  BASED ON AN INSPECTION OF THE PHYSICAL EVIDENCE AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND OTHER INFORMATION AVAILABLE TO DATE, IT IS OUR OPINION THAT THE HYDROCARBON RELEASE RESULTED FROM A SUDDEN AND UNEXPECTED MATERIAL FAILURE OF THE SHORT BYPASS HOSE BETWEEN THE TRANSFER PUMP AND THE EXTERNAL BYPASS VALVE (SEE ATTACHMENT B) LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TRANSPORT TANK.  THE HOSE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1-1/4 INCHES IN DIAMETER AND WOULD HAVE BEEN PRESSURIZED DURING THE PUMPING OPERATION TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT.  WHILE THE BYPASS HOSE WS MOSTLY CONSUMED IN THE ENSUING FIRE, THERE WAS A VARIETY OF EVIDENCE THAT INDICATED THE BYPASS HOSE WAS THE MOST LIKELY SOURCE OF THE HYDROCARBON RELEASE AND ELIMINATED OTHER EQUIPMENT AS THE SOURCE, INCLUDING THE FOLLOWING: 1. EVIDENCE OF A SUDDEN ND SIGNIFICANT RELEASE OF HYDROCARBON WAS CONSISTENT WITH THE RUPTURE OF A PRESSURIZED HOSE, NOT A LEAKING GASKET, PUMP SEAL OR VALVE PACKING.  NO RUPTURES WERE FOUND IN ANY RIGID PIPING, VALVES OR TANK NOZZLES WHICH COULD EXPLAIN THE SUDDEN HYDROCARBON RELEASE.  2. THE ACCIDENT SCENE, INCLUDING THE FIRE PATTERN, INDICATED THAT THE HYDROCARBON RELEASE WAS IN THE VICINITY OF THE BYPASS HOSE.  3.  THE FIRE, WHICH PERSISTED FOR SEVERAL HOURS AFTER IGNITION, WAS FED BY HYDROCARBON ESCAPING FROM UNDER THE MID SECTION OF THE TRANSPORT TRAILER CONSISTENT WITH THE LOCATION OF THE BYPASS HOSE.  TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS PARTICULAR TYPE OF INCIDENT MARTIN TRANSPORT INC AUDITED OUR MC331 FLEET AND REMOVED THIS TYPE OF SECONDARY BYPASS (ONLY 4 UNITS REQUIRED THIS ACTION).

TOSCO'S BAYWAY REFINERY OPERATES A FUEL TRUCK TO REFUEL PIECES OF EQUIPMENT SUCH AS CRANES AND GENERATORS, WHICH CANNOT MOVE TO A FIXED REFUELING LOCATION.  THE TRUCK LOADS AT TOSCO'S LINDEN TERMINAL WHICH IS LOCATED CONTIGUOUS TO THE REFINERY.  THE TRUCK IS VERY SIMILAR TO A HOME HEATING OIL DELIVERY TRUCK, WITH A PUMP AND 150-FT. NOZZLE-CONTROLLED HOSE AT THE REAR TO DELIVER THE FUEL.  AT THE TIME OF THE TRUCK WAS AT C PIER.  THE HOSE HAD BEEN PULLED FROM SHORE OUT ONTO THE DOCK TO REFUEL A BOOM DEPLOYMENT BOAT USED TO DEPLOY BOOM AROUND VESSELS CALLING AT THE REFINERY. THE BOATMAN NEEDED A FEW MORE INCHES TO REACH THE BOAT FUEL FILLER AND PULLED ON THE HOSE.  THE END FITTING ON THE HOSE TO WHICH THE NOZZLE ATTACHES CAME OFF THE HOSE, ALLOWING THE FUEL IN THE HOSE TO DISCHARGE ONTO THE BOATMAN AND ALSO INTO THE ARTHUR KILL.  THE OPERATOR MANNING THE TRUCK IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP ON THE TRUCK TO STOP THE DISCHARGE. ABSORBENT BOOM AND SWEEP WERE DEPLOYED TO CONTAIN AND PICK UP THE DISCHARGE.  THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED TO THE ONSITE GARAGE.  A NEW FUELING HOSE WAS INSTALLED ON THE TRUCK BEFORE IT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.  THE VENDOR THAT SUPPLIES THE HOSES RECOMMENDS THEY BE CHANGED EVERY 2 YEARS.  THE HOSE THAT FAILED HAD BEEN ON THE TRUCK FOR ONLY 10 MONTHS.  NO OTHER CORRECTIVE ACTIONS OR COUNTERMEASURES WERE TAKEN AS A RESULT OF THIS DISCHARGE.

column168: TRANSFERRING FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION FROM TANK CAR TO MC312 LINED CARGO TANK BY ATTACHING A PVC FLANGED FITTING WITH BALL VALVE TO THE UNLOADING PIPE ADAPTOR ON THE TANK CAR. CARGO HOSE WAS ATTACHED BY FOUR-BOLT FLANGE TO THE PVC COMPONENTS BOLTED TO UNLOADING PIPE ADAPTOR. THE OTHER END OF CARGO HOSE AS ATTACHED TO FILTRATION SYSTEM INLET. A CARGO HOSE FROM CARGO TANK WAS ATTACHED TO FILTRATION SYSTEM OUTLET. APPROXIMATELY 22 PSIG. AIR PRESSURE FROM A COMPRESSOR WAS APPLIED TO THE TANK CAR AND PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO THE CARGO TANK. DURING THIS TRANSFER, THE PVC FLANGE BOLTED TO THE UNLOADING PIPE ADAPTOR FAILED. PRODUCT RELEASED FROM TANK CAR UNLOADING PIPE ADAPTOR, SPRAYING INTO THE AIR AND ONTO THE ADJACENT GROUND. BULK TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL EVACUATED THE AREA AND MADE TO NOTIFICATION TO CLARK COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND BULK TRANSPORTATION. FIRE DEPARTMENT ISOLATED THE AREA AND ALLOWED THE TANK CAR TO RELEASE ALL ITS PRESSURE. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP AND REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL. BULK TRANSPORTATION HAS DISCONTINUED THE USE OF PVC OR OTHER NON-METALLIC VALVES AND FITTINGS ON TANK CAR TRANSFERS. IN ADDITION, WE ARE USING AUTOMATIC SELF-CLOSING VALVES ON PRODUCT TRANSFERS TO SHUT DOWN PRODUCT FLOW IN AN EMERGENCY.

column168: DXI (SHIPPER) WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC ABOUT 10:45 AM REGARDING AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A TRUCK (TRIMAC) OVERTURNING  IN A DITCH. SEVERAL PEOPLE FROM DXI AS WELL AS TRIMAC WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE ABOUT 150 MILES NORTH OF HOUSTON. WHILE IN ROUTE, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE STATE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT WHO INFORMED DXI PERSONNEL THAT 1500 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH. DXI THEN CONTACTED TNRCC AND NRC. TNRCC REGION 9 SENT A FIELD REPRESENTATIVE TO THE ACCIDENT SITE.  THE FIRST RESPONDERS ON THE SCENE WERE THE BRYAN/COLLEGE STATION FIRE DEPARTMENT WHICH TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE LEAKING MANWAY OF THE TANKER. WHEN DXI ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS AND NOT 1500 HAD ACTUALLY BEEN SPILLED. THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO A SMALL AREA DIRECTLY UNDER THE TRAILER. TRIMAC TRANSPORTATION CONTRACTED WITH GRONES ENVIRONMENTAL  SERVICES (WACO) TO COORDINATE THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TRANSFER FROM THE DAMAGED TRAILER AND CLEAN-UP THE SITE. THE CLEAN-UP AND TRAILER REMOVAL WAS COMPLETED AT 1:30 AM ON OCTOBER 31. GRONES IS RESPONSIBLE FOR DISPOSAL OF ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE CAUSE AS LOSS OF CONTROL OF TRUCK BY DRIVER.

PERSONNEL AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LA. DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TANK CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. UPON NOTIFICATION, UPRR MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS T.M. ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR ON TRACK 14 AT LIVONIA YARD. INSPECTION REVEALED TWO SMALL, TRAPEZOIDAL HOLES ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK, ABOUT TWO THIRDS OF THE WAY UP FROM THE BOTTOM. THE HOLES, WHICH WERE APPROXIMATELY 1/4 INCH BY 1/8TH INCH, WHEN OBSERVED, WERE ADJACENT TO THE WELD SEAM, MID WAY BETWEEN THE LADDER AND THE "A" END OF THE CAR. A SMALL, BUT STEADY STREAM OF ACID WAS TRICKLING DOWN THE TANK ONTO THE RIGHT OF WAY. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ONTO TRACK 105 WITHOUT INCIDENT. ROBINSON CONTACTED UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER WHO SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, LIVONIA FIRE DEPT., PVS CHEMICALS THE SHIPPER, AND RUBICON AT GEISMAR, LA. THE LOADERS OF THE CAR. ROBINSON CONTACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO ASSIST WITH CONTAINMENT, PRODUCT TRANSLOADING AND CLEAN UP OF SPILLAGE. L & B TRANSPORT INC. PROVIDED FIVE HIGHWAY CARGO TANKERS TO TRANSPORT THE ACID TO RUBICON AT GEISMAR, LA. THE SPILLED ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED ON SIGHT USING SODA ASH AND WATER.

UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND 3 INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES MARKED "THIS SIDE UP" ON THE TOP.  THEY TOOK ONE OF THESE BOXES OUT AND OPENED IT. THEY FOUND IT TO CONTAIN 2  X 1 L PLASTIC COATED GLASS BOTTLES.  ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN AT THE BOTTOM, LEAKING A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE FROM THE BROKEN AREA.  THEY OPENED THE REMAINING TWO BOXES AND FOUND THEM TO CONTAIN THE SAME AS THE FIRST.  ALL OF THE INNER BOXES DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL, NOR DID THE OUTER BOX.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THEIR BOXES, RESEALED THEM, AND PLACED THEM EACH INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENTS INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS FORWARDED ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS, AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WITH THE EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THIS DID NOT HAVE A PRIMARY HAZARD LABEL ON EITHER THE OUTSIDE OR INNER BOXES IT DID HAVE A CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY LABEL ON THE OUTSIDE BOX.  THIS DID NOT HAVE A PROPER SHIPPING NAME ON EITHER THE OUTSIDE OR INNER BOXES.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED "INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS", ON SIDE 2 OF PACKAGE.  ON THE TOP IT STATES "OVERPACK USED".  BOTH INNER AND OUTER BOXES HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THE INNER BOXES HAD PRE PRINTED AREA ON SIDE 1 FOR PROPER SHIPPING NAME, IDENTIFICATION NUMBER, NEITHER OF WHICH WERE FILLED OUT.  THE PROPER HAZ CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. WILDER IT WAS FOUND THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS AN IMPROPERLY PLACED SEAL. THE SHIPPER USED LATEX TO MAKE A SEAL AROUND THE MANWAY COVER, THERE WAS NO MANWAY COVER GASKET IN PLACE.  MGR WILDER REMOVED THE LATEX PRODUCT AND PLACE A NEW SEAL ON THE MANWAY COVER.  PRODUCT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR, HOWEVER, NO PRODUCT HAD REACHED THE GROUND.  MGR WILDER CALLED AND TALKED TO THE SAFETY MGR. OF MIDWEST GRAIN PRODUCTS AND EXPLAINED WHAT HE HAD FOUND.  THE SAFETY MGR. WILL MAKE AN IN HOUSE CORRECTION TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.  NO WATERWAYS OR DRAINS IN THE AREA WHERE AFFECTED.

REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, TIM O'BRIEN RESPONDED TO LEAKING TANK CAR AT ENGLEWOOD YARD.  HE DISCOVERED A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR APPROXIMATELY 1/4" IN DIAMETER.  HE PLUGGED THE HOLE AND PLACED A NEOPRENE PATCH OVER THE HOLE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED IN PLACE WITH SODA ASH.  THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED TO MATSON LEAD.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND LOCATED AN EMPTY TANKCAR. CONTENTS OF THE LEAKING CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO EMPTY TANKCAR DOWX 7954.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1130, 10/30/2000, WHILE TRAVELING THROUGH POCATELLO YARD, ED BANKS, MEFO, OBSERVED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF GATX 80830 AT A RATE OF 1 MORE DROPS PER SECOND.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 207 AT APPROXIMATE MILEPOST 214.9.  UPON CLOSED EXAMINATION, MR BANKS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE OPERATING HANDLE WAS NOT SECURED AND THE BOLTS HOLDING THE VALVE FLANGE COVER WERE NOT COMPLETELY TIGHT.  MR BANKS BROKE SIMPLOT SEAL #105326 TO REMOVE THE RETAINING TOGGLE PIN, RAISED THE HANDLE TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT POSSIBLE, INSERTED THE TOGGLE PIN AT THE HIGHER LOCATION AND APPLIED EMG SEAL #008920.  MR BANKS THEN TIGHTENED THE BOLTS SECURING THE VALVE FLANGE COVER PLATE, GAINING ABOUT ONE-HALF TURN ON EACH OF THREE BOLTS AND OVER ONE FULL TURN ON THE FOURTH BOLT.  HAVING STOPPED THE LEAK, MR BANKS THEN NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT BY APPLYING SODA ASH.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE BALLAST CRIB BETWEEN TWO TIES AND INSIDE THE GAUGE OF THE RAILS.  MR BANKS THEN DIRECTLY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER BY PHONE OF THE LEAK, THE CAUSE, AND THE ACTIONS TAKEN.

RMCC REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR SET IN TRACK 7 AT SOSAN YARD IN SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE LIQUID LINE BULL PLUG WAS LOOSE.  THE PLUG WAS SECURED WITH A 36 INCH PIPE WRENCH AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, TIM O'BRIEN WAS NOTIFIED OF LEAKING TANK CAR AND RESPONDED.  HE FOUND THE VAPOR LINE FLANGE LOOSE WITH DIRT AFFECTING THE SEAL.  HE REMOVED THE VALVE AND FLANGE, INSPECTED, CLEANED, AND REPLACED GASKET.  HE ALSO TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER NUTS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO THE BOWL TOWER.  SPILLED MATERIAL EVAPORATED BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND.

column168: RMCC REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR AT EAGLE PASS YARD.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY.  ONE ALLEN BOLT WAS LOOSE WHICH WAS CAUSING A SMALL DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THE ALLEN BOLT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

MR MIKE AVERY, MANAGER MECHANICAL CAR MAINTENANCE, CONTACTED MR JOHN STEWART, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, AT 1250 HOURS OCTOBER 11, 2000 THAT VAPOR RELEASE WAS IDENTIFIED TO BE COMING FROM THREE TANKCARS IN TRACK 209, NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD.  MR STEWART RESPONDED WITH EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND IDENTIFIED PRODUCT RELEASE AS VAPOR FROM ETCX 29072, ETCX 22045, AND ETCX 29079.  ALL THREE CARS WERE LEAKING FROM THE TOP PLUG IN THE INDUCTION VALVE FLANGE.  IN ADDITION, TANKCAR ETCX 29079 HAD TWO MANWAY BOLTS TIGHTENED.  THE THREE TANKCARS IDENTIFIED AS LEAKING WERE ISOLATED AT TRACK 717 AT THE FREIGHT HOUSE.  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND MR STEWART REMOVED THE STAINLESS STEEL PLUGS, WRAPPED THEM IN TELFON TAPE AND TIGHTENED PLUGS WITH NO FURTHER RELEASE.  RMCC WAS CONTACTED AND INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, GLENN THOMAS, DIRECTOR ENVIRONMENTAL SOUTHERN REGION, TIM O'BRIEN.  REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY SOUTHERN REGION.  MR ALVIN FREEMAN, EASTMAN KODAK OF KINGSPORT, TN, 423-229-4588, CONTACTED MR STEWART AFTER ASSESSMENT OF THE CARS AND PRIOR TO REPAIRS BEING MADE. MR STEWART NOTIFIED RMCC AT 1535 HOURS OCTOBER 11, 2000 TO CONTACT MR FREEMAN AND MR THOMAS THAT REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE AND THE CARE WERE RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

DURING THE UPLOAD ON FLIGHT 36 TO DALLAS (DAL), HOUSTON HOBBY (HOU) RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED BEADS OF MERCURY IN THE CARGO WEBBING CONNECTIONS ON THE BIN FLOOR OF THE FORWARD BIN.  THE UPLOADED BAGGAGE AND FREIGHT WERE OFFLOADED AND SET ASIDE, AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO PERFORM A MERCURY CLEAN UP WITH AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE OVERSIGHT.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE AFTER INSPECTION, AND AFTER TESTING THE BAGGAGE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SOURCE WAS HISTORICAL.  NO BAGGAGE WAS CONTAMINATED BASED ON AIR MONITORING AND VISUAL INSPECTION.  BAGGAGE WAS RELEASED TO CUSTOMERS THE FOLLOWING DAY.

column168: (A - B) TIMOTHY SMITH WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER AND HIS FORUS PINCHED A 5 LBS PLASTIC PAIL FROM UNDERNEATH THE SKID.  AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY WE PULLED THE DAMAGED PAIL AND PLACED IT IN A 55GAL RECOVERY DRUM.  WE CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  WE HOPE TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS BY RETRAINING THE DRIVER ON HOW TO PROPERLY HANDLE THE FORKLIFT.  HE WILL ALSO GET WRITTEN UP BY THE SECTOR SUPERVISOR.  MY RECOMMENDATION IS THAT THE HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HAS TO IMPROVE.

column168: 20. DESCRIBE INCIDENT IN DETAIL (IMPROPER BLOCKING, SHIPPER'S PACKAGING FAILURE, FORK-LIFT DAMAGE, PACKAGE DROPPED, ETC): XAO DSR, DAVID WEINHEIMER #87698, MADE A PICKUP OF 1 DRUM OF THE ABOVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (NMFC149980 S2, PAINT & RELATED), FROM CHEMCENTRAL THE AFTERNOON OF 10/26/00. DRUM WAS LOADED BY SHIPPER USING A FORKLIFT ATTACHMENT FROM GROUND LEVEL ONTO THE REAR OF CWCE TRL. DSR ROLLED DRUM TO FRONT OF TRL, CLOSED DOOR AND WENT ON TO HIS NEXT PICKUP AT 1550 HOURS. HE DID NOT OPEN HIS TRL DOOR AT THIS STOP ( PICKUP CANCELLED. DSR WENT TO HIS NEXT STOP AT EAGLE USA AIR, OPENING TRL DOOR, LOADING THEIR SHIPMENT, THEN NOTICING THAT DRUM WAS LEAKING AROUND BOTTOM RIM. HE NOTIFIED XAQ FOS, JIM BELL AT 1635 HOURS. SHIPPER AND CWCE SAFETY SUPV WERE IMMEDIATELY CALLED. SHIPPER AGREED TO TAKE RETURN OF DRUM, ACCEPTING AT 1720 HOURS. PER DST, APPEARS TO BE SHIPPER'S PACKAGING FAILURE. WHEN SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED AND DRUM WAS TURNED OVER HE NOTED A "SCRAPE" / "INDENTATION" ON BOTTOM OF DRUM.
DRIVER WENT TO MAKE DELIVERY.  WHEN HE TURNED THE NOZZLE ON, OIL CAME OUT OF VENT.  CUSTOMER SWITCHED OIL COMPANIES AND DID NOT CANCEL SERVICES WITH C.I.F.C.O AND TANK WAS ALREADY FULL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE TANK AND BEGAN TO MAKE DELIVERY.  HE HAD A GOOD VENT AND WHISTLE.  DURING THE DELIVERY HE HEARD A NOISE AT THE TANK AND STOPPED THE FLOW HE CHECKED TANK AND FOUND THAT EVERYTHING WAS NORMAL.  HE STARTED TO FILL THE TANK AGAIN AND HEARD THE NOISE AGAIN.  JUST A SOON AS HE STOPPED THE FLOW THE TANK RUPTURED AND THE OIL CAME POURING OUT, RUNNING OUT INTO THE ALLEY AND IN THE SEWER.  DRIVER USED HIS ABSORBENT BUT IT WASN'T NEARLY ENOUGH.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  THE BOX WAS INSPECTED AND DISCOVERED TO HAVE A LOOSE LID CLOSURE.  THERE WAS A COMMERCIAL INVOICE WITH SHIPMENT THAT STATED THE SHIPMENT  WAS PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER AND IT SHOWED THE PRODUCT TO HAVE 110 DEGREE FARENHEIT FLASHPOINT.  THERE WERE TWO OTHER PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT THAT WERE LOADED ON A TRUCK FOR (EWR) NEWARK, NJ ON AB#8210-6488-5447 & 8163-6458-4717.  THE PRODUCTS IN THOSE PACKAGES ALSO HAD FLASHPOINTS OF 130 & 102 DEGREE FARENHEIT, ACCORDING TO THE MSDS THAT WAS RECEIVED.  I NOTIFIED LOLA PAYNE AT THE EWR FEDEX FACILITY AND THE DG SPILL OFFICE WAS INSTRUCTED TO HOLD THESE TWO PACKAGES.  ANDREW JOHNSON OF THE MEM/CASFU WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PACKAGE IN THE MEM FACILITY, AND JOE CLARK OF THE EWR/CASFO WAS CALLED.  BOTH SHIPMENTS WERE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THEIR OFFICES.

FEDERAL EXPRESS AIRCRAFT #N304FE WHOSE ROUTE IS AFW TO FLL DIVERTED TO MSY BECAUSE OF  A POSSIBLE DANGEROUS GOODS THAT WAS LOADED IN THE AFT BULK CARGO COMPARTMENT.  WHILE THE PLANE WAS BEING LOADED IN AFW, ONE OF THE CARGO HANDLERS SET ASIDE THIS PIECE BECAUSE OF A "SCUBA TANK" CYLINDER IN A DUFFLE BAG.  THIS WAS TO HAVE BEEN INSPECTED IN MORE DETAIL AFTER THE AIRCRAFT WAS LOADED.  SOMEONE INADVERTANTLY LOADED THE BAG WHEN THE CARGO HANDLER WAS CALLED AWAY TO WORK IN ANOTHER AREA.  THE CREW WAS INFORMED OF THIS SITUATION AND CHOSE TO DIVERT TO MSY.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND SPECIAL AGENT JULES JOHNSON INVESTIGATED THIS SHIPMENT AT MSY. DURING HIS INVESTIGATION THE CYLINDER WAS FOUND TO NON-HAZARDOUS BECAUSE THERE WAS NO PRESSURE IN THE VESSEL.  THE FLIGHT CONTINUED TO FLL AFTER THE PACKAGE WAS OFFLOADED AND INSPECTED.

column168: RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED AN OILY SUBSTANCE ON FLOOR OF AIRCRAFT DURING THE OFFLOAD AT RDU.  UPON QUESTIONING THE CUSTOMER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS DIESEL FUEL WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM A FUEL PUMP.  CONTRACT MAINTENANCE CLEANED UP THE SMALL (APPROX. 1/2 CUP) SPILL AND RETURNED A/C TO SERVICE.  FAA CASFO WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND THE CUSTOMER WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEMS WHICH ARISE WHEN ITEMS ARE ILLEGALLY SHIPPED.  EDUCATED CUSTOMER ON THE SEVERITY OF OFFERING UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, WHICH IS THE ONLY RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS.  KEEP ON EDUCATING CUSTOMERS.

column168: EC KORY RODGERS RESPONDED TO A BAG ROOM AT PIER 7.  AN INTERNATIONAL BAG WAS FOUND TO BE SPILLING WHAT APPEARED TO BE A EPOXY RESIN SOLUTION.  EC CONTACTED OPS AND SEO SPILLED MATERIAL LABEL WAS MARITTA IN TURLUSN THE MANUFACTURE INFORMATION WAS LISTED IN TURKEY, A WARNING LABEL IN ENGLISH LISTED THE SUBSTANCE AS FLAMMABLE WITH HARMFUL VAPORS.  BAG LEAKED SUBSTANCE ON TO THE BAG BELT.  BAG BELT WAS SHUT DOWN TO PROPERLY CLEAN OR REPLACE.  SEO CONTACTED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL FOR IDENTIFICATION CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL FAA ARRIVED ON 10/6/00 TO INSPECT THE ARTICLES, CONTAINER THAT HELD SUBSTANCE AND PICK INFORMATION ON PASSENGER WHO WAS TRAVELING FROM IST TO BGI. NO PERSON WERE INJURED DUE TO THE SPILL OF THE EPOXY RESIN

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING THIRTY, TEN POUND CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT  TWO CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED AND TWENTY-EIGHT WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGED TO THE CONTAINERS WAS DUE TO TOP HEAVY FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND TWO DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWENTY-EIGHT UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON, CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON GLASS BOTTLES, WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 2.5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A 25 GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
CUSTOMER GAVE INCORRECT TANK SIZE.

column168: ON 10/17/00 AT ABOUT 0220, CRAIG CHALFANT, WAS TRYING TO LOAD PRO#126386551 ON THE REAR OF A TRAILER, WHEN CRAIG TRIED TO USE THE SIDE SHIFT ON THE TOWMOTOR, ONE OF THE RUNNERS ON THE PALLET BROKE CAUSING HIS BLADE TO COME UP AND PUNCTURE ONE OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET.  AFTER ISOLATING THE LEAK AND PUTTING FLOOR DRY ON THE SPILL, CRAIG WAS SENT TO SHOWER AND CHANGE CLOTHES AS PER THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK.  AS OF THE TIME OF THIS REPORT (0740) CRAIG HAS SAID THAT HE HAS NO ILL EFFECTS FROM THIS SPILL.

ON OCTOBER 30, 2000 RAMP AGENTS AT LAS DISCOVERED A DUFFEL BAG WITH A STRONG ODOR DURING THE UPLOAD OF SWAA FLIGHT 1601 TO CLEVELAND. THE BAG ( AND AN ADDITIONAL BOX THAT DID NOT CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ) WAS PULLED OFF THE FLIGHT AND TAKEN TO THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE.  UPON OPENING THE BAG, SIX 16-OUNCE CANS OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID (GASGACINCH)) WERE DISCOVERED.  SEVERAL ( 4 OF 6 CONTAINERS ) HAD LEAKED DURING THE FLIGHT FROM ONTARIO.  OTHER OBJECTS IN THE BAG HAD SMASHED THE CONTAINERS CAUSING THE SEAMS TO FAIL.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY 10.25.00 AT APPROXIMATELY 09:15 MR. GAMBLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON U.S. 42 JUST SOUTH OF JEROME ROAD IN UNION COUNTY, OHIO WHEN HE WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT.  THE INCIDENT INVOLVED FIVE (5) TRACTOR TRAILERS AND ONE (1) AUTOMOBILE.  THE AREA WAS COVERED WITH EARLY MORNING FOG WITH LIMITED VISIBILITY.  AS MR. GAMBLE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION THERE WERE FOUR (4) OTHER TRACTOR TRAILERS STOPPED TO MAKE A LEFT (WEST) TURN ONTO JEROME ROAD.  IT APPEARS IN ORDER TO AVOID A COLLISION, MR. GAMBLE ATTEMPTED TO MANEUVER THE MAP FUEL TRANSPORT TO THE SOUTHBOUND LANE TO AVOID CONTACT WITH THE STOPPED GRAVEL TRUCKS.  AT THE SAME TIME THERE WAS A TRACTOR TRAILER, LOADED WITH STEEL FRAME RAILS, TRAVELING SOUTH ON U.S. 42.  IN AN EFFORT TO AVOID A COLLISION, THE SOUTHBOUND STEEL TRUCK MOVED TO THE RIGHT LEAVING THE WEST SIDE OF U.S. 42.  CAUSING HIS CARGO TO BECOME DETACHED FROM THE TRAILER AND PUNCTURE MAP"S TANK TRAILER.  THIS RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK TRAILER. FOLLOWING THIS CHAIN OF EVENTS A SOUTHBOUND PASSENGER VEHICLE ON U.S. 42 BEHIND THE STEEL HAULER SLID INTO MAP'S FUEL TRANSPORT. SEVERAL SECONDS LATER THE GASOLINE IGNITED FROM AN UNKNOWN SOURCE OF IGNITION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY MARTY, MTO, EAST YARD, REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE TANK WAS WAS BEING MOVED TO CHANGE OUT THE CHASSIS, WHEN THE CRANE OPERATOR NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE IM TANK.  THE IM TANK WAS SET TO THE NEW CHASSIS, AND THE DRAYMAN HEADED FOR THE CHECKOUT GATE.  INSTRUCTIONS WERE GIVEN TO HOLD THE DRIVER AT THE GATE UNTIL THE IM TANK COULD BE INSPECTED. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOCATED THE DRIVER, WHO STATED HE HAD TIGHTENED THE MANWAY BOLTS TO SECURE THE LEAK.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE MANWAY AND FOUND THE 8 MANWAY BOLTS SECURED.  THE TANK WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES, REINSPECTED, AND NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED.  THE IM TANK WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  IN THE PROCESS OF NOTIFYING CHEMTREC PER THE 800 NUMBER ON THE WAYBILL, DEVELOPED AGMARK FOODS WAS NOT A MEMBER, AND THEREFORE, COULD NOT BE CONTACTED.  CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING DAY AND ADVISED OF THE DISCREPANCY.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RICK, SPENCE STREET YARDMASTER, EAST YARD, REPORTING A LEAKING TANKCAR.  DEVELOPED THE WEST END SWITCH JOB REPORTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO YARD TRACK 204 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED, THE BURST DISC REMOVED, AND REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 64 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE CAR SECURED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  IT APPEARS THE CAR HAD BEEN ROUGH HANDLED DURING SWITCHING, WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID TO SURGE UP THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT.  AS THE BURST DISC WAS RATED AT 80 POUNDS, THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISE THE REPLACEMENT DISC WOULD HAVE TO BE REPLACED UPON RETURN AND PRIOR TO RELOADING.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: MGR. C.T.S. R. SLOANE WAS ADVISED BY HINKLE YARD MECHANICAL FORCES THAT TANK CAR ACFX 17075, WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS IN THE ONE SPOT AT HINKLE AND CAR REPAIRMEN COULD OCCASIONALLY SMELL A "PROPANE" LIKE ODOR. MR. SLOANE RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR AND DISCOVERED THE "A" END LIQUID LINE WAS INCASED IN ICE INDICATING A RELEASE OF LIQUID PRODUCT.  THERE WERE NO FLAMMABLE VAPORS GREATER THAN 20% OF THE LEL FOR PROPANE IN THE AREA.  MR. SLOANE REMOVED THE ICE COATING THE VALVE AND DETERMINED THE VALVE SEAT WAS NOT CLOSED AND THE PACKING AROUND THE OPERATING STEM OF THE ACF ANGLE VALVE WAS LOOSE MR. SLOANE CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE PACKING.

CHRISTI HORNICK, MANAGER OF "E" FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED WALLY HAYATT, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 75198 LEAKING FROM THE TOP DOME, THREE DRIPS PER MINUTE. MGR HORNICK NOTIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE, A UPRR CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND AND INSPECT THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED AT THE WEST END BOWL STUB TRACK #74.  HAZMAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL NOTIFIED MGR HORNICK THAT THE LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE THREE FULL TURNS.  THE LIQUID LINE WAS SECURED AND THE TANK CAR RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  NO RELEASED PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.

ALL 8 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE, AND IT TOOK 2 FULL TURNS TO PROPERLY SECURE THE BOLTS. column168: MGR SNOW CALLED BY MYO ROSEVILLE ABOUT LEAKING TANK CAR ON THE SUNSET WHITNEY RANCH SIDING.  AFTER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANKCAR WAS OVERLOADED.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  COASTAL ENERGY LOCATED AT SUNSET WHITNEY AGREED TO PURCHASE THE TANK CAR FROM SINCLAIR OIL.  THE CAR WAS GIVEN TO COASTAL ENERGY FOR OFF LOADING.

WHILE DRIVER WAS MAKING A HEATING OIL DELIVERY TO A RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMER THE TANK HAD BACK PRESSURE  AND RESULTED IN A 1 GALLON SPILL OF HEATING OIL ONTO THE GROUND OF BASEMENT THIS WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR SPILL CONTRACTOR AND DISPOSED OF THIS REPORT WAS MADE INTO DOT BY A UNKNOWN PARTY.
